event: response.output_text.delta
data: {"type":"response.output_text.delta","content_index":0,"delta":".","item_id":"msg_09af40447617ee3d0169e478eaff8081958dee478d7563774f","logprobs":[],"obfuscation":"s0Inujm4iQZErNY","output_index":1,"sequence_number":621}

event: response.output_text.done
data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_09af40447617ee3d0169e478eaff8081958dee478d7563774f","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":622,"text":"### Monte Hall (3 doors) problem — logic explanation\n\n**Setup**\n- There are **3 doors**.\n- Behind **1 door** is a car (win), behind **2 doors** are goats (lose).\n- You **pick 1 door**.\n- The host, who **knows where the car is**, then opens **one of the other two doors** that has a **goat**.\n- You are offered the choice: **stay** with your original door or **switch** to the remaining unopened door.\n\n---\n\n## Step-by-step logic (no hand-waving)\n\n### 1) Your initial pick has only a 1/3 chance to be correct\nWhen you pick randomly among 3 doors:\n\n- Probability your door has the car = **1/3**\n- Probability your door has a goat = **2/3**\n\nSo at the moment you first choose, there are two equally valid cases:\n\n---\n\n### 2) Case analysis shows what the host’s action implies\n\n#### Case A: You initially picked the car (probability 1/3)\n- Your chosen door is correct.\n- The host must open a goat door among the other two.\n- If you **switch**, you will move to the only remaining goat door.\n- ✅ Switching **loses** in this case.\n\nSo:  \n- **Switch win probability given Case A = 0**\n\n---\n\n#### Case B: You initially picked a goat (probability 2/3)\n- Your chosen door is wrong.\n- That means the car is behind one of the other two doors.\n- The host opens one of the other doors that is guaranteed to be a goat.\n- After the host opens one goat, there is now only **one unopened door** besides yours, and it must contain the **car**.\n\nSo:  \n- ✅ Switching **wins** in this case\n\nTherefore:  \n- **Switch win probability given Case B = 1**\n\n---\n\n### 3) Combine the cases\nSwitching wins exactly when you were in Case B.\n\n\\[\nP(\\text{win by switching}) = P(\\text{initially picked goat}) = \\frac{2}{3}\n\\]\n\nAnd if you **stay**, you win only when you were in Case A:\n\n\\[\nP(\\text{win by staying}) = \\frac{1}{3}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## Key logical point\nThe host’s reveal is **not random**. The host **intentionally removes a goat** and always leaves your “other” unopened door to carry the remaining probability mass.\n\n- Your original door keeps its original probability: **1/3**\n- The other two doors together always had probability: **2/3**\n- The host’s action concentrates that **2/3** onto the single remaining unopened door when you switch.\n\n---\n\n### Final result\n- **Switching:** wins with probability **2/3**\n- **Staying:** wins with probability **1/3**\n\nThat’s why switching is the optimal logical strategy."}

event: response.content_part.done
data: {"type":"response.content_part.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_09af40447617ee3d0169e478eaff8081958dee478d7563774f","output_index":1,"part":{"type":"output_text","annotations":[],"logprobs":[],"text":"### Monte Hall (3 doors) problem — logic explanation\n\n**Setup**\n- There are **3 doors**.\n- Behind **1 door** is a car (win), behind **2 doors** are goats (lose).\n- You **pick 1 door**.\n- The host, who **knows where the car is**, then opens **one of the other two doors** that has a **goat**.\n- You are offered the choice: **stay** with your original door or **switch** to the remaining unopened door.\n\n---\n\n## Step-by-step logic (no hand-waving)\n\n### 1) Your initial pick has only a 1/3 chance to be correct\nWhen you pick randomly among 3 doors:\n\n- Probability your door has the car = **1/3**\n- Probability your door has a goat = **2/3**\n\nSo at the moment you first choose, there are two equally valid cases:\n\n---\n\n### 2) Case analysis shows what the host’s action implies\n\n#### Case A: You initially picked the car (probability 1/3)\n- Your chosen door is correct.\n- The host must open a goat door among the other two.\n- If you **switch**, you will move to the only remaining goat door.\n- ✅ Switching **loses** in this case.\n\nSo:  \n- **Switch win probability given Case A = 0**\n\n---\n\n#### Case B: You initially picked a goat (probability 2/3)\n- Your chosen door is wrong.\n- That means the car is behind one of the other two doors.\n- The host opens one of the other doors that is guaranteed to be a goat.\n- After the host opens one goat, there is now only **one unopened door** besides yours, and it must contain the **car**.\n\nSo:  \n- ✅ Switching **wins** in this case\n\nTherefore:  \n- **Switch win probability given Case B = 1**\n\n---\n\n### 3) Combine the cases\nSwitching wins exactly when you were in Case B.\n\n\\[\nP(\\text{win by switching}) = P(\\text{initially picked goat}) = \\frac{2}{3}\n\\]\n\nAnd if you **stay**, you win only when you were in Case A:\n\n\\[\nP(\\text{win by staying}) = \\frac{1}{3}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n## Key logical point\nThe host’s reveal is **not random**. The host **intentionally removes a goat** and always leaves your “other” unopened door to carry the remaining probability mass.\n\n- Your original door keeps its original probability: **1/3**\n- The other two doors together always had probability: **2/3**\n- The host’s action concentrates that **2/3** onto the single remaining unopened door when you switch.\n\n---\n\n### Final result\n- **Switching:** wins with probability **2/3**\n- **Staying:** wins with probability **1/3**\n\nThat’s why switching is the optimal logical strategy."},"sequence_number":623}

